  <H1>Dynamical Systems Framework for Neuroscience</H1>

  <Body>Neuronal behavior can be precisely characterized as trajectories in state space, where understanding attractors and basins reveals how neurons respond to stimuli and return to rest. This lesson establishes the mathematical foundation that underlies all subsequent neuronal modeling in this course.</Body>

  <H2>What is a Dynamical System?</H2>

  <Body>A dynamical system is a mathematical framework that describes how the state of a system evolves over time according to fixed rules. In the context of neuroscience, dynamical systems provide the language to describe how membrane potentials, ion channel states, and other neuronal variables change moment by moment.</Body>

  <Body>Formally, a continuous-time dynamical system is defined by an ordinary differential equation (ODE) of the form:</Body>

  <Code lang="plaintext">
dx/dt = f(x, t)
  </Code>

  <Body>Here, x represents the state vector (which could include membrane voltage, gating variables, calcium concentrations, etc.), t is time, and f is a function that specifies the instantaneous rate of change of the state. The function f encapsulates all the biophysical rules governing the system.</Body>

  <Body>When f does not depend explicitly on time (only on x), we call the system autonomous:</Body>

  <Code lang="plaintext">
dx/dt = f(x)
  </Code>

  <Body>Autonomous systems are particularly important in neuroscience because they capture intrinsic neuronal dynamics independent of time-varying external inputs.</Body>

  <FlashCard id="fc-dynamical-system">
    <Front>What is a dynamical system in mathematical terms?</Front>
    <Back>A system described by dx/dt = f(x, t), where x is the state vector and f specifies how the state evolves over time according to fixed rules.</Back>
  </FlashCard>

  <H2>State Space and Trajectories</H2>

  <Body>The state space (or phase space) is the set of all possible states a system can occupy. Each dimension of the state space corresponds to one state variable. For a neuron described by its membrane voltage V alone, the state space is one-dimensional (the real line). For the Hodgkin-Huxley model with voltage V and three gating variables m, h, n, the state space is four-dimensional.</Body>

  <Body>A trajectory (or orbit) is the path traced out in state space as time progresses from some initial condition x(0) = x_0. Mathematically, a trajectory is the solution x(t) to the differential equation with specified initial conditions.</Body>

  <Code lang="python">
import numpy as np
from scipy.integrate import odeint
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Simple 1D linear system: dV/dt = -(V - V_rest) / tau
def membrane_dynamics(V, t, V_rest, tau):
    return -(V - V_rest) / tau

# Parameters
V_rest = -70  # mV (resting potential)
tau = 10      # ms (membrane time constant)

# Simulate trajectories from different initial conditions
t = np.linspace(0, 50, 500)
initial_conditions = [-90, -80, -60, -50, -40]

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
for V0 in initial_conditions:
    V = odeint(membrane_dynamics, V0, t, args=(V_rest, tau))
    plt.plot(t, V, label=f'V(0) = {V0} mV')

plt.axhline(y=V_rest, color='k', linestyle='--', label='V_rest')
plt.xlabel('Time (ms)')
plt.ylabel('Membrane Voltage (mV)')
plt.title('Trajectories Converging to Resting Potential')
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()
  </Code>

  <Body>The code above demonstrates trajectories in a one-dimensional state space. Regardless of initial condition, all trajectories converge to the resting potential V_rest. This convergence behavior is the hallmark of a stable attractor.</Body>

